                <h2>1. Know Your Passenger Rights</h2>
                <p>Airlines owe some obligations to passengers for delayed or cancelled flights. But the important part is to know your rights to get fair treatment.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>EU Regulations:</b> In general, for EU passengers, as per EU Regulation 261/2004, passengers might be entitled to compensation for delays (more than three hours’ worth) or cancellations unless it is due to some extraordinary circumstances, such as bad weather.</li>
                    <li><b>US Regulations:</b> There will be the give an airline ticket refund to a passenger for the cancellation or substantial change of flights. However, compensation is less regulated for delays and varies widely based on the airlines.</li>
                    <li><b>Policies of Airlines:</b> Each airline has a different set of terms and conditions covering delays and cancellations. They elaborate on entitlement for fares, rebooking, and refund eligibility. Some airlines may provide meal vouchers or accommodation for delays, while others provide limited services.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Bookmark FaresMatch to compare it easily with other airline policies and stay updated about your rights.</p>


                <h2>2. React Quickly: Contact Your Airline</h2>
                <p>The delay or cancellation of the flight should incite a sudden rush of activity to up one’s chance of receiving the best possible results.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Types of contact:</b> You should call the airline customer service the moment the announcement is made about the delay or cancellation. Fast forward to one’s chances of getting an early rebooking or compensation.</li>
                    <li><b>Services:</b> Go for all channels to reach the airline. Many such airlines have a comparatively faster response time towards requests sent via their applications or social media sites as opposed to traditional telephones. Some also offer online rescheduling or refund facilities.</li>
                    <li><b>Try Alternatives:</b> Ask for the next available flight on any airline. If rebooking isn’t possible, inquire about refunds or vouchers for future travel. Accommodation and Transport Assistance: Overnight delays: Ask for accommodation as well as ground transport.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>FaresMatch gives you live updates on airline schedules, which will help you make your decisions faster.</p>


                <h2>3. Utilize Travel Insurance</h2>
                <p>Travellers can rest easy knowing they are financially and psychologically protected against possible delays and cancellations by purchasing travel insurance. A complete travel insurance policy includes:</p>
